## ITERATION 41 BODY

title: "041 — Rebuild Vehicle Marker Proportions (Large Operational Ring)"
description: "Redesign the vehicle marker to use a larger outer ring and clearer visual hierarchy so vehicles read as spatial entities rather than small pins."

:::GOALS

Rebuild the vehicle marker proportions so the outer ring becomes a meaningful visual layer similar to the reference UI.

The marker must communicate three things clearly:

1. vehicle identity
2. vehicle presence on the map
3. vehicle heading

The outer ring must be large enough to create spatial presence and negative space around the center marker.

This iteration is focused on correcting marker proportions, not experimenting with multiple heading variants.

:::END

:::TASKS

Modify the existing `VehicleMarker` component so the marker structure follows a three-layer hierarchy.

Layer 1 — Center vehicle body
- Render the vehicle identity glyph in the center.
- The glyph must remain the fastest element to recognize.
- Preserve existing glyph readability and contrast against satellite terrain.

Layer 2 — Expanded operational ring
- Increase the outer ring diameter substantially (approximately 2.5×–3× the current circumference).
- The ring must read as a separate visual layer surrounding the vehicle body.
- Maintain a noticeable gap between the center body and the outer ring to create negative space.
- Preserve status coloring behavior for normal, degraded, critical, and offline states.

Layer 3 — Heading indicator
- Keep a single heading treatment (do not render multiple variants).
- The heading indicator must rotate with vehicle heading.
- It must remain secondary to the center identity glyph.
- The heading indicator should sit within the space between the center marker and the outer ring.

Adjust marker layout so the center marker, heading indicator, and outer ring do not visually compete.

Do not modify the map engine, route rendering, panels, or fleet list as part of this iteration.

Ensure the marker remains readable both when viewing a single vehicle and when multiple vehicles are visible on screen.

:::END

:::ACCEPTANCE

- Vehicle markers have a noticeably larger outer ring than before.
- The outer ring reads as a meaningful spatial layer rather than a decorative border.
- The center glyph remains the quickest element to recognize.
- Heading is visible but does not compete with the identity glyph.
- Multiple vehicles on screen still feel balanced and readable.

:::END